 Online Games -- t9. The Effective Use of a 3D Virtual World in a JFL Classroom: Evidence from Discourse Analysis -- t10. Game-Mediated Activities in JFL Classrooms: Considerations and Issues in Learning, Teaching and Implementation -- tPart 5: Technology Beyond the Physical Classroom -- t11. Distance Learning and Asynchronous Communication While on Study Abroad: Conversation for- Learning and Journal Reflections as a Means to Enhance Language Use -- t12. Learners’ Participation in Japanese-Related Online Communities and the Relationship between Online Activities and Classroom Learning: A Comparative Case Study of Two JFL Learners -- tEpilogue -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book addresses several pressing concerns of teachers and researchers who are looking for ways to integrate technology use in and out of their classrooms and assess its usefulness in the learning process. It provides an up-to-date examination of technology-supported pedagogy and language acquisition in a variety of Japanese as a foreign or second language contexts. It equips readers with practical pedagogical information, including methods of implementation and learning assessment, and ideas for how technology can be applied to achieve a wide range of learning objectives. The topics examined include cultural learning, identity construction, speaking, reading, writing, pronunciation, collaborative online learning, digital and 3D virtual reality games, online text analysis, and participation in online communities. In addition, different e-learning configurations such as flipped, online, and distance learning classrooms are explored. Studies examine various current technologies (e.g. blogs, synchronous/asynchronous telecollaboration, corpus analysis software, modern pronunciation tools) and will have both direct and indirect consequences for teaching and learning a second/foreign language with technology across all languages.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aJapanese languagexComputer-assisted instruction for foreign speakers. 0aJapanese languagexStudy and teachingxForeign speakers. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Study & Teaching.2bisacsh  aCALL.  aComputer Assisted Language Learning.  aJFL.  aJSL.  aJapanese as a second language.  aJapanese pedagogy.  aSLA.  acollaborative online learning.  ae-learning.  alanguage acquisition.  ateaching and learning Japanese.  atechnology-supported pedagogy.1 aAkiyama, Yuka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBushnell, Cade, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiBello Takeuchi, Jae, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHayashi, Hisako, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHomma, Tae, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKomori, Saeko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLangton, Nina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLanigan, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcMeekin, Abigail, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcMeekin, Abigail, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNiendorf, Mariya Aida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSakai, Takako, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShintaku, Kayo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTakamiya, Yumi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTsuda, Asami, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYamada, Toru, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.l